{"title_page": "Steve Bruce", "text_new": "{{pp-protected|small=y}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{featured article}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Steve Bruce\n| image          = Steve Bruce.jpg\n| image_size     = \n| caption        = Bruce managing [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] in 2011\n| fullname       = Stephen Roger Bruce<ref name=Hugman>{{Hugman|2533|accessdate=28 May 2019}}</ref>\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1960|12|31|df=y}}<ref name=Hugman/>\n| birth_place    = [[Corbridge]], England\n| height         = {{height|ft=6|in=0}}<ref>{{cite book |editor-last=Sewell |editor-first=Albert |title=News of the World Football Annual 1996\u201397 |publisher=Invincible Press |year=1996 |page=401 |isbn=978-0-00-218737-4}}</ref>\n| position       = [[Centre-back]]<ref name=Hugman/>\n| currentclub    = [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] (manager)\n| youthyears1    = 1977\u20131979 |youthclubs1 = [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]]\n| years1         = 1979\u20131984 |clubs1 = [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]]               |caps1 = 205 |goals1 = 29\n| years2         = 1984\u20131987 |clubs2 = [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]]           |caps2 = 141 |goals2 = 14\n| years3         = 1987\u20131996 |clubs3 = [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] |caps3 = 309 |goals3 = 36\n| years4         = 1996\u20131998 |clubs4 = [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]]     |caps4 = 72  |goals4 = 2\n| years5         = 1998\u20131999 |clubs5 = [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]]   |caps5 = 10  |goals5 = 0\n| totalcaps      = 737 |totalgoals = 81<!-- LEAGUE ONLY -->\n| nationalyears1 = 1979\u20131980 |nationalteam1 = [[England national under-18 football team|England Youth]] |nationalcaps1 = 8 |nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 1987      |nationalteam2 = [[England national football B team|England B]]            |nationalcaps2 = 1 |nationalgoals2 = 0\n| manageryears1  = 1998\u20131999 |managerclubs1 = [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]]\n| manageryears2  = 1999\u20132000 |managerclubs2 = [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]]\n| manageryears3  = 2001      |managerclubs3 = [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]]\n| manageryears4  = 2001      |managerclubs4 = [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]]\n| manageryears5  = 2001\u20132007 |managerclubs5 = [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]]\n| manageryears6  = 2007\u20132009 |managerclubs6 = [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]]\n| manageryears7  = 2009\u20132011 |managerclubs7 = [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]]\n| manageryears8  = 2012\u20132016 |managerclubs8 = [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]]\n| manageryears9  = 2016\u20132018 |managerclubs9=  [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]]\n| manageryears10 = 2019     |managerclubs10= [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]]\n| manageryears11 = 2019\u2013     |managerclubs11= [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]]\n}}\n'''Stephen Roger Bruce''' (born 31 December 1960) is an English professional [[Manager (association football)|football manager]] and former [[Football player|player]] who played as a [[centre-back]]. He is the current manager of [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]].\n\nBorn in [[Corbridge]], Northumberland, he was a promising schoolboy footballer but was rejected by several professional clubs. He was on the verge of quitting the game altogether when he was offered a trial with [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]]. Bruce was offered an apprenticeship and went on to play more than 200&nbsp;games for the club before joining [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]] in 1984, winning the [[1985 Football League Cup Final|League Cup in 1985]]. In 1987, he moved to [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]], with whom he achieved great success, winning twelve trophies including three [[Premier League]] titles, three [[FA Cup]]s, one [[EFL Cup|League Cup]] and the [[European Cup Winners' Cup]]. He also became the first English player of the 20th century to captain a team to [[Double (association football)|the Double]]. Despite his success on the field, he was never selected to play for the [[England national football team|England national team]]. Commentators and contemporaries have described him as one of the best English players of the 1980s and 1990s never to play for his country at full international level.\n\nBruce began his managerial career with [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]], and spent short periods of time managing [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]], [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]] and [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] before joining [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] in 2001. He twice led Birmingham to [[Promotion and relegation|promotion]] to the Premier League during his tenure of nearly six years, but resigned in 2007 to begin a second spell as manager of Wigan. At the end of the [[2008\u201309 in English football|2008\u201309 season]] he resigned to take over as manager of [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]], a post he held until he was dismissed in November 2011. Seven months later, he was appointed manager of [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]] and led the club to two promotions to the Premier League, as well as the [[2014 FA Cup Final]], before leaving in July 2016. He took over at [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] four months later but was dismissed in October 2018. He took over as manager of Sheffield Wednesday in February 2019 and left in July that year to take over at Newcastle United.<ref name=\"newcastle-appoint\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2019/jul/17/newcastle-appoint-steve-bruce-manager-rafael-benitez|title=Newcastle appoint Steve Bruce as manager to succeed Rafael Ben\u00edtez|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=17 July 2019|accessdate=17 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n[[File:corbridge uk.jpg|thumb|left|[[Corbridge]], Bruce's place of birth]]\n\nBruce was born in [[Corbridge]] in Northumberland, the elder of two sons of Joe and Sheenagh Bruce.<ref>Bruce (1994), p. 33.</ref> His father was local, and his mother had been born in [[Bangor, County Down|Bangor]] in Northern Ireland.<ref name=\"Ireland\">{{cite news |first=Ian |last=Parkes |title=Blues defender Bruce opts for green shirt of Ireland |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2006/feb/23/newsstory.sport3 |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |date=23 February 2006 |accessdate=5 January 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Vital\">{{cite news |title=Bruce in the middle |newspaper=Evening Star |location=Ipswich |url=http://www.eveningstar.co.uk/content/eveningstar/sport/story.aspx?brand=ESTOnline&category=Sport&tBrand=estonline&tCategory=Sport&itemid=IPED04%20Sep%202007%2009%3A37%3A27%3A587 |date=4 September 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080610191103/http://www.eveningstar.co.uk/content/eveningstar/sport/story.aspx?brand=ESTOnline&category=Sport&tBrand=estonline&tCategory=Sport&itemid=IPED04%20Sep%202007%2009%3A37%3A27%3A587 |archivedate=10 June 2008}}</ref> The family lived in Daisy Hill near [[Wallsend]],<ref>Bruce (1994), p. 34.</ref> and Bruce attended [[Benfield School]].<ref name=\"SB38\">Bruce (1994), p. 38.</ref>\n\nBruce, a boyhood fan of [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]], said that he sneaked into [[St James' Park]] without paying to watch the team play, saying \"I have always been a [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]] lad and when I was a kid, I crawled under the turnstiles to get in to try and save a [[Shilling|bob]] or whatever it was. They were my team, I went to support them as a boy and being a [[Geordie]] it's in-bred, you follow the club still the same today.\"<ref name=\"ManU\">{{cite web |title=Tyne Travellers: Part I |url=http://www.manutd.com/en/News-And-Features/Features/2006/Oct/Tyne-Travellers-Part-I.aspx?pageNo=3 |publisher=Manchester United F.C. |accessdate=7 January 2016 |date=3 October 2006}}</ref> Like several other future professionals from the area,<ref name=\"MULeg\" /> he played football for [[Wallsend Boys Club]].<ref name=\"ManU\" /> He was also selected for the Newcastle Schools representative team, and at the age of 13 was among a group of players from the team selected to serve as [[ball boy]]s at the [[1974 Football League Cup Final|1974 League Cup Final]] at [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley Stadium]].<ref name=\"SB74\">Bruce (1994), p. 74.</ref>\n\nHaving been turned down by several professional clubs, including Newcastle United, [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]], [[Derby County F.C.|Derby County]] and [[Southport F.C.|Southport]], Bruce was about to start work as an apprentice plumber at the [[Swan Hunter]] dockyard when he was offered a trial by [[Football League Third Division|Third Division]] club [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]], whose manager [[Gerry Summers]] had seen him playing for Wallsend in an international youth tournament.<ref name=\"SB39\">Bruce (1994), pp. 39\u201340.</ref> He travelled down to [[Kent]] with another player from the Wallsend club, [[Peter Beardsley]], but although Gillingham signed Bruce as an apprentice, they turned Beardsley away.<ref name=\"Buster2\" /> At the time Bruce was playing as a [[midfielder]], but he was switched to the centre of defence by the head of Gillingham's youth scheme, [[Bill Collins (footballer, born 1920)|Bill Collins]], whom Bruce cites as the single biggest influence on his career.<ref name=\"Buster2\">{{cite web |first=Haydn |last=Parry |title=Past Players: Steve Bruce |url=http://www.gillinghamfootballclub.premiumtv.co.uk/page/PastPlayersDetail/0,,10416~63313,00.html |publisher=Gillingham FC |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070503105625/http://www.gillinghamfootballclub.premiumtv.co.uk/page/PastPlayersDetail/0%2C%2C10416~63313%2C00.html |archivedate=3 May 2007 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"Buster\">{{cite news |title=Adams and Bruce were Buster's premier pupils |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/main.jhtml?xml=/sport/2004/03/07/sfnpb207.xml |date=6 March 2004 |first=Patrick |last=Barclay |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071118132027/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/main.jhtml?xml=%2Fsport%2F2004%2F03%2F07%2Fsfnpb207.xml |archivedate=18 November 2007 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Playing career==\n===Gillingham===\n[[File:Priestfield1.jpg|thumb|[[Priestfield Stadium]], home of [[Gillingham F.C.|Gillingham]], where Bruce began his playing career]]\n\nBruce spent the [[1978\u201379 in English football|1978\u201379 season]] in Gillingham's [[reserve team]] and, despite playing in defence, scored 18&nbsp;goals to finish the season as top scorer.<ref name=\"triggs\">Triggs (2001), p. 70.</ref> In January 1979, he was selected to represent the [[England national under-18 football team|England youth]] team, and he went on to gain eight caps, participating in the [[1980 UEFA European Under-18 Championship]].<ref name=\"SB52\">Bruce (1994), pp. 52\u201353.</ref> He came close to making his debut for the club's senior team in May 1979, but Summers decided at the last minute that, as Gillingham were chasing [[Promotion and relegation|promotion]] from the Third Division, Bruce was not yet ready to handle the pressure of the occasion.<ref name=\"SB53\">Bruce (1994), p. 53.</ref> He eventually made his senior debut in a [[EFL Cup|League Cup]] tie against [[Luton Town F.C.|Luton Town]] on 11 August 1979,<ref name=\"First season\" /> and made an immediate impact in the team, winning the club's Player of the Year award at the end of the [[1979\u201380 in English football|1979\u201380 season]].<ref name=\"SB57\">Bruce (1994), p. 57.</ref> He went on to make more than 200&nbsp;appearances for the club,<ref name=\"triggs\"/> and was twice voted into the [[Professional Footballers' Association]]'s Third Division Team of the Year.<ref name=\"triggs352\">Triggs (2001), p. 352.</ref>\n\nConfident that he was being targeted by clubs from higher divisions, Bruce resolved not to sign a new contract with Gillingham when his existing deal expired at the end of the [[1983\u201384 in English football|1983\u201384 season]].<ref name=\"SB60\">Bruce (1994), p. 60.</ref> In an April 1983 match against [[Newport County A.F.C.|Newport County]], he attempted, in a moment of anger, to deliberately injure opposition player [[Tommy Tynan]], but connected awkwardly and succeeded only in breaking his own leg, leaving him unable to play again for six months.<ref name=\"SB62\">Bruce (1994), p. 62.</ref> He returned in time to play a key role in Gillingham achieving two draws against [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] in the [[FA Cup]] in 1984, attracting the attention once again of [[scout (sport)|scouts]] from [[Football League First Division|First Division]] clubs.<ref name=\"Buster2\" /> [[Arthur Cox (footballer)|Arthur Cox]], manager of Bruce's beloved Newcastle United, expressed an interest in signing the player, but resigned from his job before any further action could be taken.<ref name=\"SB65\">Bruce (1994), p. 65.</ref> Bruce eventually opted to sign for [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]] in August 1984 for a fee variously reported as \u00a3125,000<ref name=\"sang\">{{cite web |url=http://www.soccerbase.com/teams/team.sd?season_id=114&team_id=1855&teamTabs=transfers&season_id=114 |title=Transfers: 1984/85 |work=Soccerbase |publisher=Centurycomm |accessdate=4 January 2016}}</ref> or \u00a3135,000.<ref name=\"triggs\" /> In 2009, he was voted into Gillingham's [[Gillingham F.C. Hall of Fame|Hall of Fame]].<ref name=\"GFCHOFR\">{{cite web |url=http://www.gillinghamfootballclub.com/page/NewsDetail/0,,10416~1725855,00.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091202174319/http://www.gillinghamfootballclub.com/page/NewsDetail/0%2C%2C10416~1725855%2C00.html |archivedate=2 December 2009 |title=GFC Hall of Fame Winners |publisher=Gillingham F.C. |date=18 July 2009 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Norwich City===\n[[File:SteveBruceNorwich1980s.JPG|thumb|right|upright|Bruce pictured circa 1986, during his time with [[Norwich City F.C.|Norwich City]]]]\n\nBruce began the [[1984\u201385 in English football|1984\u201385 season]] by scoring an [[own goal]] in the first minute of his debut for Norwich against [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/2327277/Steve-Bruce-helps-Wigan-Athletic-stop-the-rot.html |title=Steve Bruce helps Wigan Athletic stop the rot |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |first=James |last=Mossop |accessdate=5 January 2016 |date=2 December 2007 |location=London}}</ref> but went on to score the team's winning goal in the semi-final of the League Cup against local rivals [[Ipswich Town F.C.|Ipswich Town]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AWNB:BSMB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0FE5660E1AA4DC79&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB57AB53DF815 |newspaper=Sunday Mercury |location=Birmingham |title=Sunday Mercury: Football: I want my Blues to be a working class act |date=19 October 2003 |first=Ian |last=Clarkson |accessdate=6 January 2016}}</ref> and was named man of the match in Norwich's victory in [[1985 Football League Cup Final|the final]].<ref name=\"LC85\">{{cite news |url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AWNB:LSTB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=10035F1CCC279CE7&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB57AB53DF815 |title=Norwich win the League Cup, 1985 \u2013 Caught in time |newspaper=The Sunday Times |location=London |date=28 September 2003 |accessdate=6 January 2016}}</ref> Bruce was voted [[Norwich City Player of the Year]], but the team was [[Promotion and relegation|relegated]] to the [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]].<ref name=\"Ash\">{{cite news |first=David |last=Miller |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/2359353/Ashton-the-only-difference-for-anxious-Norwich.html |title=Ashton the only difference for anxious Norwich |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |date=8 May 2005 |accessdate=10 September 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.canaries.premiumtv.co.uk/page/History/0,,10355~1132064,00.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080109004921/http://www.canaries.premiumtv.co.uk/page/History/0%2C%2C10355~1132064%2C00.html |archivedate=9 January 2008 |title=Player of the Season 1967\u20132007 |publisher=Norwich City FC |date=25 January 2008 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Bruce played in every match as Norwich won promotion back to the top division at the first time of asking in the [[1985\u201386 in English football|1985\u201386 season]],<ref name=\"Ash\" /><ref name=\"2D\">{{cite book |first1=Bill |last1=Bateson |first2=Albert |last2=Sewell |title=News of the World Football Annual 1986/1987 |publisher=Harper Collins |year=1986 |isbn=0-85543-076-1 |page=281}}</ref> after which he was chosen to replace the departing [[Dave Watson]] as club [[Captain (sports)|captain]].<ref name=\"SB85\">Bruce (1994), p. 85.</ref> The following season he helped the club to its highest ever league finish of fifth position.<ref name=\"8695history\">{{cite web |url=http://www.canaries.premiumtv.co.uk/page/History/0,,10355~1025327,00.html |title=History \u2013 1986\u20131995 |publisher=Norwich City FC |date=15 May 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080109004911/http://www.canaries.premiumtv.co.uk/page/History/0%2C%2C10355~1025327%2C00.html |archivedate=9 January 2008 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 1987, he was chosen to captain the [[England national football B team|England B team]] in a match against the [[Malta national football team|full national team of Malta]],<ref name=\"SB88\">Bruce (1994), p. 88.</ref> but it was to be his only appearance in an England shirt, and he has subsequently been described as one of the best defenders of his era never to be selected for [[England national football team|the full England team]].<ref name=\"MattU\">{{cite news |title=Football: Upson's choice puts the down days in the past |newspaper=The Independent |accessdate=28 September 2007 |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/upsons-choice-puts-the-down-days-in-the-past-122952.html |date=16 March 2003 |first=Alex |last=Hayes |quote=Steve Bruce showed that you can be one of the best defenders of your generation and yet never play for your country. |location=London}}</ref><ref name=\"fi\">{{cite news |title=Football: Steve Bruce's Path to Top |newspaper=Sunday Mirror |location=London |accessdate=4 September 2008 |url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Football%3A+STEVE+BRUCE'S+PATH+TO+TOP.-a0121623995 |quote=From there he moved to Norwich City before making the move to Manchester United that established him as the best uncapped English defender of his generation. |date=5 September 2004}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |first=Bryan |last=Robson |title=Robbo: My Autobiography |publisher=Hodder & Stoughton |year=2007 |isbn=0-340-83957-0 |page=118 |quote=There's no doubt he was one of the best English players not to be capped by his country}}</ref> Bruce later stated, \"I bumped into former England manager [[Bobby Robson]] in [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]]'' (sic)''. He came up to me and said 'I should have capped you'. It was nice to hear but it still didn't get me one .... I'll always be a little disappointed I didn't get one.\"<ref name=\"champs\">{{cite book |first=Frank |last=Malley |title=Champions: The Story of Manchester United's Winning Season |publisher=Simon & Schuster |year=1993 |isbn=0-671-85264-7 |page=131}}</ref>\n\nBruce began to attract the attention of big-name clubs in late 1987, with [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]], [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]], [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] and [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]] all reported to be interested in signing him.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AWNB:LTIB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0F90F17B5C631ABA&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB57AB53DF815 |title=Football: Bruce offer rejected |newspaper=The Times |location=London |date=9 December 1987 |accessdate=6 January 2016}}</ref> Manchester United quickly emerged as the front runners for his signature, and Bruce publicly expressed his desire to sign for the club.<ref>{{cite news |title=Football: Bruce deal is not dead |newspaper=The Times |location=London |date=11 December 1987}}</ref> The deal came close to collapsing when Norwich asked for a transfer fee of \u00a3900,000 after initially agreeing to accept \u00a3800,000,<ref name=\"gone\" /> leading to Bruce refusing to play any further matches for the club, which he felt was jeopardising his dream move.<ref name=\"SB93\">Bruce (1994), p. 93.</ref> On 17 December 1987, shortly before his 27th birthday, the deal was concluded and Bruce officially left [[Carrow Road]],<ref name=\"gone\">{{cite news |url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AWNB:LTIB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0F90F18B42CD6904&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB57AB53DF815 |title=Football: Bruce deal agreed after late hitch |newspaper=The Times |location=London |date=18 December 1987 |first=Ian |last=Ross |accessdate=6 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AWNB:LTIB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0F90F185DBF4CEE8&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB57AB53DF815 |title=Football: Transfer shelved yet again |newspaper=The Times |location=London |date=15 December 1987 |first=Ian |last=Ross |accessdate=6 January 2016}}</ref> for a fee reported as \u00a3800,000<ref name=\"sang\" /> or \u00a3825,000.<ref name=\"MULeg\">{{cite web |url=http://www.manutd.com/en/Players-And-Staff/Legends/Steve-Bruce.aspx |title=Legends: Steve Bruce |publisher=Manchester United F.C. |accessdate=7 January 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160105193503/http://www.manutd.com/en/Players-And-Staff/Legends/Steve-Bruce.aspx |archivedate=5 January 2016 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Norwich fans remembered his contribution, and in 2002 voted him into the [[List of Norwich City F.C. Hall of Fame members|Norwich City Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.edp24.co.uk/Content/Sport/CanaryCentenary/HallofFame.asp |title=Norwich City Hall of Fame |newspaper=Eastern Daily Press |location=Norwich |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927172948/http://www.edp24.co.uk/Content/Sport/CanaryCentenary/HallofFame.asp |archivedate=27 September 2007}}</ref>\n\n===Manchester United===\nBruce made his Manchester United debut in a 2\u20131 win over [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]] on 19 December 1987,<ref name=\"all\" /> and played in 21 of United's remaining 22&nbsp;league fixtures,<ref name=\"all2\">{{cite web |url=http://www.stretfordend.co.uk/seasons/season1988.html |title=Season 1987/88 |publisher=StretfordEnd.co.uk |accessdate=8 September 2008}}</ref> helping the club to a top two place in the First Division for the first time since 1980.<ref name=\"FCHDMU\">{{cite web |url=http://www.stretfordend.co.uk/competitions/league.html |title=United in the League |publisher=StretfordEnd.co.uk |accessdate=12 September 2008}}</ref> The team only finished in mid-table in the following season,<ref name=\"FCHDMU2\">{{cite web |url=http://www.statto.com/football/teams/manchester-united/1988-1989/table |title=Manchester United 1988\u20131989: Table: Final Table |publisher=Statto Organisation |accessdate=4 January 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160107075528/http://www.statto.com/football/teams/manchester-united/1988-1989/table |archivedate=7 January 2016}}</ref> prompting manager [[Alex Ferguson]] to bring in several new players, including [[Gary Pallister]], who joined the club in August 1989 from [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]].<ref name=\"IP2\">Ponting (2000), p. 193.</ref> His partnership with Bruce in the centre of defence was described in 2006 by the then-United captain, [[Gary Neville]], as the best in the club's history.<ref>{{cite news |first=Gary |last=Neville |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/football/premier_league/manchester_united/article744420.ece |title=If we sign another right back, he had better be good |newspaper=The Times |location=London |date=23 March 2006 |accessdate=8 September 2008 |url-access=subscription }}</ref> \"Dolly and Daisy\", as the pair were affectionately known, are described as \"arguably the best\" on the official Manchester United website.<ref>{{cite web |last=Pallister |first=Gary |title=Players and Staff: Legends |url=http://www.manutd.com/en/Players-And-Staff/Legends/Gary-Pallister.aspx |publisher=Manchester United F.C. |accessdate=11 February 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150211181218/http://www.manutd.com/en/Players-And-Staff/Legends/Gary-Pallister.aspx |archivedate=11 February 2015 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Bruce and Pallister were part of the team that won the [[1990 FA Cup Final]] against [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] in a replay.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thefa.com/TheFACup/FACompetitions/TheFACup/History/HistoryOfTheFACup/1990ManchesterUnitedCrystalPalace |archiveurl=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20120816014012/http://www.thefa.com/Competitions/FACompetitions/TheFACup/History/HistoryOfTheFACup/1990ManchesterUnitedCrystalPalace |url-status=dead |archivedate=16 August 2012 |title=Classic Cup Finals: 1990 |publisher=The Football Association |accessdate=8 September 2008}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the lifting of the five-year ban on English clubs from European competitions, which had been imposed after the [[Heysel Stadium disaster]], United became England's first entrants into the [[European Cup Winners' Cup]] in the [[1990\u201391 European Cup Winners' Cup|1990\u201391 season]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Bateson |first1=Bill |first2=Albert |last2=Sewell |title=News of the World Football Annual 1990\u201391 |publisher=Invincible Press |year=1990 |page=129 |isbn=0-85543-207-1}}</ref> Bruce played regularly, and scored three goals, in the team's progress to [[1991 European Cup Winners' Cup Final|the final]] against [[FC Barcelona]].<ref name=\"stret91\">{{cite web |url=http://www.stretfordend.co.uk/seasons/season1991.html |title=Season 1990/91 |publisher=StretfordEnd.co.uk |accessdate=9 September 2008}}</ref> He came close to scoring the first goal, only for [[Mark Hughes]] to deflect the ball over the line and claim the goal,<ref name=\"CWC\">{{cite news |url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AWNB:LTIB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0F91EC6FB2495ECE&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB57AB53DF815 |title=Hughes provides the spark \u2013 Football |newspaper=The Times |location=London |first=Stuart |last=Jones |date=16 May 1991 |accessdate=6 January 2016}}</ref> and United went on to win the game 2\u20131. This was a particularly high-scoring season for Bruce, who found the net 13&nbsp;times in the First Division and 19&nbsp;times in total in all competitions.<ref name=\"stret91\" /> He also played again at Wembley, in the [[1991 Football League Cup Final|League Cup final]], in which United were defeated by [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]] of the Second Division.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AWNB:LTIB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0F91EBE8777636A6&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB57AB53DF815 |title=Sheridan strike wreaks havoc on sickly rivals \u2013 Football |newspaper=The Times |location=London |first=Stuart |last=Jones |date=22 April 1991 |accessdate=6 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Steve Bruce at the cliff -march 92.JPG|thumb|upright|Bruce pictured in 1992, during his time at [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]]]\n\nBruce missed several weeks of the [[1991\u201392 in English football|1991\u201392 season]] when he underwent an operation on a longstanding [[hernia]] problem,<ref name=\"recovery\">{{cite news |url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AWNB:LTIB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0F91F31CE8BD228C&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB57AB53DF815 |title=Bruce resolves to make a swift recovery \u2013 Football |newspaper=The Times |location=London |first=Stuart |last=Jones |date=24 January 1992 |accessdate=6 January 2016}}</ref> in which [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]], after a season-long tussle, beat Manchester United to the championship by four points.<ref>Bateson and Sewell (1992), pp. 54, 309\u2013311.</ref> Bruce helped United win their first-ever League Cup in April 1992,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AWNB:LTIB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0F91F3766191D329&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB57AB53DF815 |title=McClair sets up bid for double \u2013 Football |newspaper=The Times |location=London |first=Stuart |last=Jones |date=13 April 1992 |accessdate=6 January 2016}}</ref> captaining the team in [[1992 Football League Cup Final|the final]] in place of the injured [[Bryan Robson]].<ref>Bateson and Sewell (1992), p. 91.</ref> Injuries continued to take their toll upon Robson during the [[1992\u201393 in English football|1992\u201393 season]], leading to Bruce captaining the team in the majority of United's matches during the first season of the new [[Premier League]].<ref name=\"champs\" /> Bruce scored two late goals in a win over Sheffield Wednesday which proved decisive in United winning the inaugural Premier League title,<ref>{{cite news |first=David |last=Hytner |url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:UKNB:GRDC&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=120165B21DB30ED0&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=86AB2B3721534D07B61270632E6A70BE |title=Football: Chelsea's title hopes wrecked by Heskey: Chelsea 1 Wigan Athletic 1 Essien 55 Heskey 90 |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |date=15 April 2008 |accessdate=6 January 2016}}</ref> the first time the club had won the championship of English football since 1967, and he and Robson received the trophy jointly after the home victory over [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] on 3 May.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AWNB:LTIB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0F91FAE6DEFF4AA0&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB57AB53DF815 |title=Old Trafford stands united in celebration \u2013 Football |newspaper=The Times |location=London |first=Rob |last=Hughes |date=4 May 1993 |accessdate=6 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nAt the height of his success with United, Bruce was contacted by [[Jack Charlton]], manager of the [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland national team]], who had discovered that, due to his mother's place of birth, Bruce was eligible to play for Ireland. Bruce states in his autobiography that further investigation revealed that, while his earlier appearance for England B in a [[Exhibition game|friendly match]] was not an issue, his appearances for the England Youth team in a [[UEFA]]-sanctioned tournament prohibited him from playing for the senior team of another country.<ref name=\"SB89\">Bruce (1994), p. 89.</ref> He has subsequently claimed that he chose not to play for Ireland as it would have caused problems for his club at a time when UEFA restricted the number of foreign players that a club could have in their squad in its competitions.<ref name=\"Ireland\" />\n\nUnited dominated English football in the [[1993\u201394 in English football|1993\u201394 season]], winning a second consecutive Premier League title and then defeating Chelsea in the [[1994 FA Cup Final|FA Cup final]] to become only the fourth team, and Bruce the first English captain, to win [[Double (association football)|The Double]] in the 20th century,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AWNB:LTIB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0F924217D546CF4E&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB57AB53DF815 |title=United worthy of place among elite \u2013 FA Cup |newspaper=The Times |location=London |first=Rob |last=Hughes |date=16 May 1994 |accessdate=6 January 2016}}</ref><ref>The other 20th-century Double-winning captains were [[Dave Mackay]] and [[Alan Hansen]], both from Scotland, and [[Danny Blanchflower]] from Northern Ireland.</ref><ref name=\"SB1\">Bruce (1994), p. 1.</ref> The [[1994\u201395 in English football|1994\u201395 season]] was a disappointing one for Bruce and United, as the club failed in its bid to win a third consecutive Premier League title and lost to Everton in the [[1995 FA Cup Final|FA Cup final]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AWNB:LTIB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0F9247A0E0BFBA03&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB57AB53DF815 |title=Everton's Royle revival crowned by Rideout \u2013 Football |newspaper=The Times |location=London |first=Rob |last=Hughes |date=22 May 1995 |accessdate=6 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nDuring the following season Bruce was offered the job of manager by three clubs, but Ferguson refused to allow him to pursue the opportunities as he felt the player still had a role to play in the United team.<ref>{{cite news |first=David |last=Harrison |url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:UKNB:LNWB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0F933E6886339C7E&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=86AB2B3721534D07B61270632E6A70BE |title=Gissa job, says Bruce \u2013 Football |newspaper=News of the World |location=London |date=16 November 1997 |accessdate=6 January 2016}}</ref> Bruce made a further 30&nbsp;Premier League appearances,<ref name=\"all\">{{cite web |url=http://www.stretfordend.co.uk/playermenu/bruce.html |title=Steve Bruce |publisher=StretfordEnd.co.uk |accessdate=4 January 2016}}</ref> as United managed to overcome a 12-point deficit to Newcastle United to win the championship once again.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.premierleague.com/page/1995/96Season |title=Season 1995/96 |publisher=Premier League |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111030075007/http://www.premierleague.com/page/1995/96Season |archivedate=30 October 2011}}</ref> A week later he was left out of United's squad for the [[1996 FA Cup Final|FA Cup final]] due to a slight injury.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/keanes-lack-of-practice-fails-to-worry-ferguson-61273.html |title=Keane's lack of practice fails to worry |newspaper=The Independent |first=Tim |last=Rich |accessdate=6 January 2016 |date=19 May 2004 |location=London}}</ref> At the end of the match [[Eric Cantona]], who had captained the team and scored the only goal in a 1\u20130 win over Liverpool, attempted to persuade Bruce to be the one to receive the trophy, but Bruce declined.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AWNB:LNWB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0F933F0CE3D601CF&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB57AB53DF815 |title=Man U-fique! \u2013 It's Doubly bubbly for king Eric |newspaper=News of the World |location=London |first=Alex |last=Montgomery |date=12 May 1996 |accessdate=6 January 2016}}</ref> Ferguson denied that Bruce's omission was a sign that his time at the club was nearing an end,<ref name=\"Leaving MU\" /> but Bruce, then 35&nbsp;years old, believed that he would be unlikely to be selected for the team during the year remaining on his contract.<ref name=\"Leaving MU2\">{{cite news |first=Neil |last=Custis |url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:UKNB:LSNB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0F93499D929A3445&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=86AB2B3721534D07B61270632E6A70BE |title=I'll be the most hated man at Elland Road \u2013 and I'm gonna love it \u2013 Exclusive |newspaper=The Sun |location=London |date=14 February 1998 |accessdate=6 January 2016}}</ref> He opted instead to join First Division club [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] on a [[Free transfer (association football)|free transfer]], having signed a contract valued at nearly \u00a32&nbsp;million over two years, which made him one of the highest-paid players in the country.<ref name=\"Leaving MU\">{{cite news |url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AWNB:LTIB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0F9249CB8DE3A931&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB57AB53DF815 |title=United's route to Champions' League made easy \u2013 Football |newspaper=The Times |location=London |date=23 May 1996 |first=Peter |last=Ball |accessdate=6 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Later playing career===\nBruce was among five former Premier League players signed by Birmingham manager [[Trevor Francis]] to add experience to a squad expected to challenge for promotion.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Trev-ing+up+for+glory!-a061158554 |title=Trev-ing up for glory! |first=Hugh |last=Southon |newspaper=Sunday Mirror |location=London |date=18 August 1996 |accessdate=21 November 2007}}</ref> He was made captain of the team,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AWNB:LTIB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0F924BB205098E44&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated4&req_dat=0D0CB57AB53DF815 |title=Options for boss of Birmingham City |first=Jason |last=Nisse |newspaper=The Times |location=London |date=19 February 1997 |accessdate=6 January 2016}}</ref> but his Birmingham career was dogged by a series of disagreements with Francis.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Blue+revolt.-a061160305 |title=Blue revolt |newspaper=Sunday Mirror |location=London |date=24 November 1996 |accessdate=21 November 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AWNB:LSNB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0F9350E2A80979EB&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated4&req_dat=0D0CB57AB53DF815 |title=Bruce snubs age concern |newspaper=The Sun |location=London |date=28 December 1996 |accessdate=6 January 2016}}</ref> Director [[David Sullivan (businessman)|David Sullivan]] felt the need to publicly deny rumours that Bruce was lined up to replace Francis as manager after the club's stock market flotation.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/market-report--hello-dolly-as-biotechs-dance-back-into-the-spotlight-1280742.html |title=Market report : Hello Dolly as biotechs dance back into the spotlight |first=Patrick |last=Tooher |newspaper=The Independent |date=26 February 1997 |accessdate=21 November 2007 |location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AWNB:LTIB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0F924BBC1019468B&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated4&req_dat=0D0CB57AB53DF815 |title=Francis sees stock tumble among supporters |first=Richard |last=Hobson |newspaper=The Times |location=London |date=1 March 1997 |accessdate=6 January 2016}}</ref> While playing for Birmingham, Bruce was the subject of several bids from his old Manchester United colleague Bryan Robson to sign for Middlesbrough, but the transfer never happened.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Robbo+in+for+Bruce.-a061061044 |title=Robbo in for Bruce |newspaper=Daily Mirror |location=London |date=22 August 1997 |accessdate=3 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe [[1997\u201398 in English football|1997\u201398 season]] saw Bruce dropped for the first time in his career, for a match against former club Gillingham, and he described himself as \"hurt and unhappy\" at being left out.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:UKNB:LSNB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0F934D28F220CE22&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated4&req_dat=86AB2B3721534D07B61270632E6A70BE |title=Bruce axe was right, says Trev |newspaper=The Sun |location=London |date=14 August 1997 |accessdate=6 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:UKNB:LSNB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0F934D37FA95C8CF&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated4&req_dat=86AB2B3721534D07B61270632E6A70BE |title=Welcome back, Bruce |newspaper=The Sun |location=London |date=23 August 1997 |accessdate=6 January 2016}}</ref> By November 1997 he was being left out more frequently, and his omission against [[Nottingham Forest F.C.|Nottingham Forest]] provoked a public war of words, which fuelled rumours that the manager was to be dismissed and that Bruce would take over as caretaker until the end of the season.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/CAMPBELL'S+KINGDOM.-a061118833 |title=Campbell's kingdom |first=Phil |last=Rostron |newspaper=Sunday Mirror |location=London |date=16 November 1997 |accessdate=26 November 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/BRUCE+SET+TO+BOSS+BLUES!%3B+But+Rudge+is+next+in+line.-a061118701 |title=Bruce set to boss Blues! |first=Hugh |last=Southon |newspaper=Sunday Mirror |location=London |date=23 November 1997 |accessdate=26 November 2007}}</ref> At the end of the season he accepted the post of [[player-manager]] of [[Sheffield United F.C.|Sheffield United]]. Though the deal was delayed while Birmingham attempted to negotiate a transfer fee for his playing contract,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-united-move-to-keep-kidd-from-everton-1167652.html |title=United move to keep Kidd from Everton |first=Alan |last=Nixon |newspaper=The Independent |location=London |date=26 June 1998 |accessdate=26 November 2007}}</ref> he took up his new position on 2 July 1998.<ref name=\"Managers: Steve Bruce\"/> He played 11 matches for the club before retiring as a player, his final appearance being in a home match against Sunderland on 28 November 1998.<ref name=\"Games played by Steve Bruce in 1998/1999\"/>\n\n==Style of play==\nDuring the early part of his career, Bruce's sometimes over-enthusiastic playing style, which he later described as \"rampaging\",<ref name=\"Buster2\" /> caused him disciplinary problems. He later developed into a solid and dependable all-round player, characterised as \"an honest trier who made the absolute most of limited natural ability\".<ref name=\"IP\">Ponting (2000), p. 177.</ref> In his prime, he was particularly noted for his calm and deliberate passing of the ball, and his ability to control it under pressure, often with his chest. At the time, [[Mark Wright (footballer, born 1963)|Mark Wright]] of Liverpool was said to be the only other centre-back able to match Bruce's level of skill in these areas.<ref name=\"recovery\" />\n\nBruce was also known for his unusually high goalscoring rate for a centre-back, resulting from a combination of his ability to powerfully head the ball and his effectiveness in taking [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty kick]]s.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.setanta.com/Templates/News/NewsArticle.aspx?id=8896&epslanguage=EN |publisher=Setanta Sports |title=The XI at 11: Goalscoring centre backs |first=Adam |last=Marshall |date=2 October 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303192952/http://www.setanta.com/Templates/News/NewsArticle.aspx?id=8896&epslanguage=EN |archivedate=3 March 2016}}</ref> Although lacking poise and grace,<ref name=\"IP\" /> and often criticised for his lack of pace,<ref name=\"IP\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AWNB:LTIB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0F924308782B4AB3&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB57AB53DF815 |newspaper=The Times |location=London |title=Cantona key to United's ignition \u2013 Football |first=Rob |last=Hughes |date=23 November 1994 |accessdate=6 January 2016}}</ref> his bravery and willingness to take knocks from opposition players made him the \"heart\" of the defence during his time with Manchester United.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/vidic-succeeds-as-king-bruce-1004983 |newspaper=Manchester Evening News |title=Vidic succeeds as king Bruce |first=Mike |last=Whalley |date=22 September 2007 |accessdate=5 January 2016}}</ref> He was well known for continuing to play even when injured,<ref name=\"IP\" /><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/story/sport/qlkfsnmhql/rss2/ |newspaper=Irish Examiner |location=Cork |title=Masked ball for 50 in-a-row 'Killer' |first=Liam |last=Mackey |date=10 September 2008 |accessdate=5 January 2016 |quote=But Steve Bruce \u2013 I think he played with 20 broken bones!}}</ref> including returning to the United team at short notice in 1992 even though he was awaiting an operation on a hernia.<ref name=\"recovery\" /> His indomitable spirit and motivational abilities were deemed vital to the United team,<ref name=\"IP\" /> and Alex Ferguson has commented on his \"determination and heart\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.fifa.com/world-match-centre/news/newsid/657/703/index.html |publisher=FIFA |title=Fergie compares captain Rooney to greats |date=11 December 2007 |accessdate=5 January 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160107075527/http://www.fifa.com/world-match-centre/news/newsid/657/703/index.html |archivedate=7 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Managerial career==\n===Early managerial career===\nIn his first season as a manager, Bruce guided Sheffield United to eighth place in the First Division, nine points away from a place in the play-offs.<ref>{{cite web |title=England 1998/99 |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablese/eng99.html |publisher=Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation |date=20 December 1999 |accessdate=6 September 2008}}</ref> He caused controversy when he attempted to take his team off the pitch during an FA Cup match against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]]. Bruce felt that the Gunners had broken an unwritten rule of sportsmanship by scoring the winning goal from a throw-in instead of returning the ball to United, who had intentionally kicked it out of play to allow an injured player to be attended to. Although the game eventually continued to a finish, following a gesture by Arsenal the match was declared void and replayed.<ref>{{cite news |first=Russell |last=Kempson |title='The goal was an accident. I am sorry' \u2013 Football |url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AWNB:LTIB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0F9297FD631FE04C&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB57AB53DF815 |newspaper=The Times |location=London |date=15 February 1999 |accessdate=6 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first=Matt |last=Barlow |title=Fifa Green Light Clears Blades For Rematch |url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AWNB:BPOC&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0F6F676921B27E2F&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB57AB53DF815 |newspaper=Birmingham Post |date=23 February 1999 |accessdate=6 January 2016}}</ref> In May 1999, Bruce resigned from his post after just one season in charge, citing turmoil in the club's boardroom and a shortage of funds for transfers.<ref>{{cite news |first=Alan |last=Nixon |title=Football: Bruce walks out of Wigan for Palace |url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AWNB:TND1&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=132A8CB31EBC7050&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB57AB53DF815 |newspaper=The Independent |location=London |date=30 May 2001 |accessdate=6 January 2016}}</ref> He contemplated leaving football for a job in television but was persuaded by [[Huddersfield Town A.F.C.|Huddersfield Town]] owner Barry Rubery to become the club's manager.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Football: Bruce out on the town: Steve has high hopes at Huddersfield |newspaper=Sunday Mirror |location=London |date=5 December 1999 |first=Brian |last=McNally}}</ref>\n\nHuddersfield were early promotion contenders in the [[1999\u20132000 in English football|1999\u20132000 season]], winning six consecutive matches to rise to third place in the First Division table by late November,<ref>{{cite news |first=Christopher |last=Irvine |title=Grey days serve to inspire Bruce \u2013 Football Saturday |url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AWNB:LTIB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0F92999760CF415B&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB57AB53DF815 |newspaper=The Times |location=London |date=27 November 1999 |accessdate=6 January 2016}}</ref> but lost form and failed to reach the [[EFL Championship play-offs|play-offs]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Nick |last=Szczepanik |title=Bruce reflects after Fulham give taste of things to come \u2013 Football |url=http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AWNB:LTIB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=0F929B9660072A53&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0D0CB57AB53DF815 |newspaper=The Times |location=London |date=8 May 2000 |accessdate=6 January 2016}}</ref> The team continued to struggle at the start of the [[2000\u201301 in English football|2000\u201301 season]], gaining just six points from 11 matches, and Bruce was sacked in October 2000.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Bruce sacked by Huddersfield |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_1/974836.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |date=16 October 2000 |accessdate=18 November 2007}}</ref> He then became involved in a dispute with Rubery, who accused him of \"wasting\" \u00a33m on players and having \"an ego to feed\".<ref>{{Cite news |title=Bruce accused of 'wasting' \u00a33m |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/h/huddersfield_town/1204598.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |date=6 March 2001 |accessdate=28 February 2008}}</ref> Although he was linked with the manager's job at [[Queens Park Rangers F.C.|Queens Park Rangers]],<ref>{{Cite news |title=QPR suffer Bruce snub |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/q/qpr/1182049.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |date=21 February 2001 |accessdate=28 February 2008}}</ref> Bruce remained out of the game until he was appointed manager of [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]] in April 2001.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Wigan appoint Bruce |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/w/wigan_athletic/1260445.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |date=4 April 2001 |accessdate=18 November 2007}}</ref> The team reached the Second Division play-offs but lost in the semi-finals,<ref>{{Cite news |title=Whelan hits out at Bruce departure |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/w/wigan_athletic/1357970.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |date=31 May 2001 |accessdate=28 February 2008}}</ref> and Bruce almost immediately left the club, where he had been in charge for less than two months, to take over as manager of Crystal Palace.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Bruce takes up Palace post |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/c/crystal_palace/1362215.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |date=31 May 2001 |accessdate=18 November 2007}}</ref>\n\nAlthough his new club began the [[2001\u201302 in English football|2001\u201302 season]] strongly, topping the First Division table and looking well placed for regaining the Premier League place that the club had last held in the 1997\u201398 season,<ref name=\"hurry\">{{Cite news |title=A man in a hurry |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_1/1632611.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |date=2 November 2001 |accessdate=29 February 2008}}</ref> Bruce tendered his resignation less than three months into the season in order to return to Birmingham City as manager. Although he was initially prevented from doing so by an injunction taken out by Crystal Palace, he was eventually allowed to join the Midlands-based club after a compensation package was agreed.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Birmingham unveil Bruce |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/birmingham_city/1704971.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |date=12 December 2001 |accessdate=18 November 2007}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Bruce eyes promotion |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/birmingham_city/1706536.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |date=12 December 2001 |accessdate=28 February 2008}}</ref> By now he had acquired a reputation as a manager who rarely held down a job for a significant length of time.<ref name=\"hurry\" />\n\n===Birmingham City===\n[[File:Steve Bruce pre-season Germany 2004.jpg|thumb|upright|Bruce managing [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] in 2004]]\n\nUpon his arrival, the Blues were in a mid-table position in the First Division,<ref>{{Cite news |title=Former Blues: Jeff Kenna |url=http://www.bcfc.com/page/WhereAreTheyNowDetail/0,,10412~1054686,00.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090515155958/http://www.bcfc.com/page/WhereAreTheyNowDetail/0%2C%2C10412~1054686%2C00.html |archivedate=15 May 2009 |publisher=Birmingham City F.C. |url-status=dead}}</ref> but a lengthy unbeaten run saw the team qualify for the play-offs.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Bruce feels true Blue |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/birmingham_city/1975644.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |date=8 May 2002 |accessdate=8 September 2008}}</ref> The team went on to beat Bruce's former club Norwich City in the final after a [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalty shoot-out]] to gain promotion to the Premier League, ending a 16-year absence from the top level of English football.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Birmingham spot on to deny the Canaries |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2002/may/13/match.sport3 |newspaper=The Guardian |date=13 May 2002 |accessdate=5 January 2016 |first=Dominic |last=Fifield |location=London}}</ref> Birmingham spent the early part of the [[2002\u201303 in English football|2002\u201303 season]] struggling near the foot of the Premier League table, but Bruce's signing of [[Christophe Dugarry]] revitalised the team, who ended the season in 13th place and finished higher than local rivals [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] for the first time since the 1970s.<ref>{{cite web |title=Birmingham Season Guide |url=http://www.espnfc.co.uk/story/271942/birmingham-season-guide |publisher=ESPN FC |date=9 August 2003 |first=Dale |last=Johnson |accessdate=8 September 2008}}</ref>\n\nThe following season began well for Birmingham, who climbed as high as fourth in the table, but the team's fortunes declined and they could only finish in tenth place at the end of the season.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Taylor hunts European spot |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/birmingham_city/3886253.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |date=12 July 2004 |accessdate=8 September 2008}}</ref> Despite this disappointment, Bruce signed a new contract in June 2004 designed to keep him at [[St Andrew's (stadium)|St Andrew's]] for a further five years,<ref>{{Cite news |title=Football: Newcastle set to sign Milner as Bruce opts to stay at City |newspaper=The Independent |location=London |first=Tim |last=Rich |date=30 June 2004}}</ref> but just two months later [[Freddy Shepherd]], chairman of Newcastle United, was reported to have made Bruce his main target in the search for a new manager to replace Bobby Robson. The club was reportedly prepared to pay Birmingham more than \u00a33&nbsp;million in compensation, and Bruce himself was said to be keen to take over at St James' Park,<ref>{{Cite news |title=Bruce the target as Venables 'shunned' |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/2386029/Bruce-the-target-as-Venables-shunned.html |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |first=Rob |last=Stewart |date=3 September 2004 |accessdate=6 January 2016 |location=London}}</ref> but he ultimately remained at Birmingham. He stated that \"as far as I'm concerned, I've got a job to do [at Birmingham City] and I'm determined to get on with it\", but it was also reported that Newcastle would have been required to pay a much larger compensation fee or face legal action had he been persuaded to switch clubs.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Newcastle scramble to find Robson replacement |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/premier-league/newcastle-scramble-to-find-robson-replacement-558471.html |newspaper=The Independent |date=31 August 2004 |first=Jason |last=Burt |accessdate=6 January 2016 |location=London}}</ref> Initial expectations were high for the [[2004\u201305 in English football|2004\u201305 season]], but the club once again finished in a mid-table position, ending the season in 12th&nbsp;place.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Premiership review season 2004/5 |first=Phil |last=McNulty |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/4555281.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |date=17 May 2005 |accessdate=8 September 2008}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the sacking of [[Graeme Souness]] as Newcastle manager in February 2006, Bruce was again linked with the job,<ref>{{Cite news |title=Newcastle sack Souness |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2006/feb/02/newsstory.sport13 |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |date=2 February 2006 |accessdate=5 January 2016}}</ref> which ultimately went to [[Glenn Roeder]].<ref>{{Cite news |title=Roeder named as Newcastle manager |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/n/newcastle_united/4770157.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |date=16 May 2006 |accessdate=5 September 2008}}</ref> By this stage of the [[2005\u201306 in English football|2005\u201306 season]], Birmingham were struggling in the league, and on 21 March 2006 were beaten 7\u20130 at home by Liverpool in the FA Cup quarter-finals.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Birmingham 0\u20137 Liverpool |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/birmingham_city/4831306.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |date=21 March 2006 |accessdate=21 February 2008}}</ref> Some supporters of the club began to call for his resignation, but Bruce insisted that he would fight on as manager.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Bruce vows to carry on as manager |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/birmingham_city/4831306.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |date=22 March 2006 |accessdate=21 February 2008}}</ref> The team managed to climb out of the relegation zone for the first time in nearly six months after a win over [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]] in early April 2006.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Birmingham 1\u20130 Bolton |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/4867430.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |date=4 April 2006 |accessdate=8 September 2008}}</ref> However, they were soon overtaken by Portsmouth, whose victory over Wigan Athletic on 29 April left Birmingham mathematically unable to match their points total and therefore relegated.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Birmingham and Baggies relegated |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/4958306.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |date=29 April 2006 |accessdate=6 September 2008}}</ref>\n\nAlthough Bruce had the largest transfer budget in the division made available to him,<ref>{{Cite news |title=Birmingham issue finance warning |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/birmingham_city/6682979.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |date=23 May 2007 |accessdate=8 September 2008}}</ref> Birmingham made a slow start to the [[2006\u201307 in English football|2006\u201307 season]] in the [[EFL Championship|Championship]] and, after a 1\u20130 defeat at home to Norwich City, the team's fifth consecutive match without a win, there were calls from fans and local journalists for the manager to be sacked.<ref name=\"Gold\">{{Cite news |first=Colin |last=Tattum |title=David Gold: I've lost a friend in Steve Bruce |url=http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/david-gold-ive-lost-a-friend-61587 |newspaper=Birmingham Post |date=11 April 2008 |accessdate=5 January 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Gold2\">{{cite news |first=Colin |last=Tattum |title=Blues 0 Norwich 1 |url=http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/blues-0-norwich-1-27047 |newspaper=Birmingham Mail |date=17 October 2006 |accessdate=5 January 2016}}</ref> Bruce publicly accepted responsibility for the team's poor run and admitted that he feared for his job,<ref name=\"Fear\">{{Cite news |first=Lee |last=Reynolds |title=Birmingham 0\u20131 Norwich |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/top-stories/2006/10/18/birmingham-0-1-norwich-115875-17949008/ |newspaper=Daily Mirror |location=London |date=18 October 2006 |accessdate=5 September 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090615194734/http://www.mirror.co.uk/news/top-stories/2006/10/18/birmingham-0-1-norwich-115875-17949008/ |archivedate=15 June 2009}}</ref> but the team responded with a 1\u20130 victory over Derby County,<ref name=\"chant\">{{cite news |first=Mike |last=Baker |title=Bruce wins the latest battle in Birmingham's uncivil war |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2006/oct/23/match.sport2 |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |date=23 October 2006 |accessdate=5 January 2016}}</ref> and then recorded a further five consecutive league victories to be joint leaders of the league table by late November.<ref name=\"top\">{{Cite news |title=Burnley 1 Birmingham City 2: Bendtner's guile brings best out of Birmingham |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/football-league/burnley-1-birmingham-city-2-bendtners-guile-brings-best-out-of-birmingham-426001.html |newspaper=The Independent |date=27 November 2006 |first=David |last=Instone |accessdate=5 September 2008 |location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Birmingham City 2006\u20132007: Results |url=http://www.statto.com/football/teams/birmingham-city/2006-2007/results |publisher=Statto Organisation |accessdate=4 January 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160107075528/http://www.statto.com/football/teams/birmingham-city/2006-2007/results |archivedate=7 January 2016}}</ref> On 29 April 2007, Birmingham secured promotion to the Premier League, with one match to play, by virtue of Derby County's 2\u20130 defeat at Crystal Palace. Chairman [[David Gold (businessman)|David Gold]] told the press \"There have been some dark days but Steve has been outstanding. He was determined to bounce back. He has rebuilt the team and now we are all back where we want to be.\"<ref>{{Cite news |title=Birmingham & Sunderland promoted |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_div_1/6605665.stm |publisher=BBC Sport |date=29 April 2007 |accessdate=4 September 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Wigan Athletic===\nIn May 2007, Birmingham's board agreed a new contract for Bruce, but the unwillingness of the club's prospective purchaser [[Carson Yeung]] to ratify it left his future uncertain.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/birmingham_city/7028493.stm |title=Bruce fears for Birmingham future |publisher=BBC Sport |date=4 October 2007 |accessdate=16 November 2007}}</ref> In October 2007, Bolton Wanderers were refused permission to speak to him about their managerial vacancy.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/football/premier_league/bolton/article2686670.ece |title=Steve Bruce emerges as Bolton Wanderers target |newspaper=The Times |location=London |date=18 October 2007 |accessdate=16 November 2007 |url-access=subscription }}</ref>\nLater that month, Bruce and Yeung held a meeting which reportedly had positive results.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/birmingham_city/7066956.stm |title=Yeung moves to calm Bruce fears |publisher=BBC Sport |date=29 October 2007 |accessdate=16 November 2007}}</ref> Bruce later claimed that Birmingham's managing director [[Karren Brady]] had \"shafted\" him on a new contract with the club,<ref>{{cite news |first=James |last=Hunter |url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/sunderland-afc/safc-news/2009/10/26/steve-bruce-blasts-back-at-karen-brady-72703-25016549 |title=Steve Bruce blasts back at Karen Brady |newspaper=Evening Chronicle |location=Newcastle upon Tyne |date=26 October 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120418203549/http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/sunderland-afc/safc-news/2009/10/26/steve-bruce-blasts-back-at-karen-brady-72703-25016549/ |archivedate=18 April 2012}}</ref> and when Wigan Athletic requested permission to speak to Bruce about their managerial vacancy, he was receptive to their approach.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2007/nov/19/newsstory.birminghamcityfc |title=Birmingham in a flux as Bruce heads for Wigan |first=Stuart |last=James |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |date=14 November 2007 |accessdate=5 January 2016}}</ref> As required under the terms of his contract, Wigan agreed to pay Birmingham a then-[[Transfer (association football)#Managers|world record]] compensation for the loss of his services of around \u00a33m,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/b/birmingham_city/7100525.stm |title=Bruce set to join Wigan Athletic |publisher=BBC Sport |date=18 November 2007 |accessdate=18 November 2007}}</ref> and they were then allowed to speak to him. On 19 November, Wigan announced the signing of Bruce for a second time.<ref name=left_Birmingham_BBC>{{cite news |title=Bruce leaves Birmingham for Wigan |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=19 November 2007 |date=19 November 2007 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/w/wigan_athletic/7100525.stm}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 November, during a press conference which was intended to formally present Bruce as the new manager of Wigan, the club's chief executive Brenda Spencer informed the media that the deal had been put on hold by \"unknown issues\" between Bruce and Birmingham City, reported to centre on the advance payment of the image rights element of Bruce's contract at St Andrew's.<ref name=left_Birmingham_BBC2>{{cite news |title=Bruce's Wigan move hit by hold-up |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=21 November 2007 |date=21 November 2007 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/w/wigan_athletic/7105078.stm}}</ref><ref name=imagerights>{{cite news |first1=Andy |last1=Hunter |first2=Stuart |last2=James |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2007/nov/22/newsstory.birminghamcityfc |title=Bruce's move to Wigan held up over image-rights dispute |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |date=21 November 2007 |accessdate=5 January 2016}}</ref> On 23 November 2007 Wigan announced that Bruce had now signed his contract and would officially rejoin the Latics.<ref name=BBCconfirmWigan>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/w/wigan_athletic/7105078.stm |title=Bruce confirmed as Wigan manager |publisher=BBC Sport |date=23 November 2007 |accessdate=4 January 2016}}</ref> His first game in charge was a 1\u20131 home draw with [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]] on 1 December 2007.<ref name=firstgameback>{{cite news |first=Duncan |last=MacKay |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2007/dec/02/match.wiganathletic |title=Bruce is buoyed by Wigan's fightback |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |date=2 December 2007 |accessdate=5 January 2016}}</ref> Wigan spent the remainder of the season struggling against relegation, but the club secured Premier League survival with victory over Aston Villa in the penultimate game of the season.<ref name=BBCWigan>{{cite news |first=David |last=Lacey |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2008/may/05/premierleague.astonvilla |title=Bruce kisses his own feat in guiding Wigan to safety |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |date=5 May 2008 |accessdate=5 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.statto.com/football/teams/wigan-athletic/2007-2008/results |title=Wigan Athletic 2007\u20132008: Results |publisher=Statto Organisation |accessdate=4 January 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160107075528/http://www.statto.com/football/teams/wigan-athletic/2007-2008/results |archivedate=7 January 2016}}</ref> In September 2008, Bruce was once again linked with the manager's job at Newcastle United following the departure of [[Kevin Keegan]].<ref name=LEP>{{cite news |url=http://www.lep.co.uk/sport/bruce-back-in-race-for-hotseat-1-79998 |title=Bruce back in race for hotseat |newspaper=Lancashire Evening Post |location=Preston |date=26 September 2008 |accessdate=5 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nBruce led Wigan to an 11th-place finish in the 2008\u201309 season,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.statto.com/football/teams/wigan-athletic/2008-2009/results |title=Wigan Athletic 2008\u20132009: Results |publisher=Statto Organisation |accessdate=5 January 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160107075528/http://www.statto.com/football/teams/wigan-athletic/2008-2009/results |archivedate=7 January 2016}}</ref> despite the loss of midfielder [[Wilson Palacios]] to Tottenham Hotspur in the January transfer window.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/2009/01/16/tottenham-tie-up-wilson-palacios-deal-steve-bruce-bemoans-loss-of-right-arm-115875-21045598/ |title=Tottenham tie up Wilson Palacios deal; Steve Bruce bemoans loss of \"right arm\" |newspaper=Daily Mirror |location=London |date=16 January 2009 |accessdate=27 May 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090625235151/http://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/2009/01/16/tottenham-tie-up-wilson-palacios-deal-steve-bruce-bemoans-loss-of-right-arm-115875-21045598/ |archivedate=25 June 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Sunderland===\n[[File:Mikel Arteta 2 (6270706966).jpg|thumb|Bruce managing [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] in 2011]]\n\nOn 27 May 2009, Bruce was reported to have been given permission to talk to Sunderland about succeeding [[Ricky Sbragia]], who resigned as manager after the last match of the season.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/s/sunderland/8069299.stm |title=Bruce cleared to meet Sunderland |publisher=BBC Sport |date=27 May 2009 |accessdate=27 May 2009}}</ref> Bruce was confirmed as the new manager of Sunderland on 3 June after signing a three-year contract.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/teams/s/sunderland/8080762.stm |title=Bruce named as Sunderland manager |date=3 June 2009 |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=3 June 2009}}</ref> He was joined at Sunderland by three of his former Wigan Athletic coaching staff, assistant [[Eric Black]], goalkeeping coach [[Nigel Spink]], and reserve team coach [[Keith Bertschin]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/football/premier_league/sunderland/article6424687.ece |title=Sunderland confirm appointment of Steve Bruce as manager |newspaper=The Times |location=London |date=3 June 2009 |accessdate=3 June 2009 |url-access=subscription }}</ref> In his first season at Sunderland, despite a run of 14 games without a win, Bruce led the Black Cats to a 13th-place finish in the Premier League.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11695_6150521,00.html |title=Sunderland review |publisher=Sky Sports |date=13 May 2010 |accessdate=23 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nBruce made wholesale changes to Sunderland's squad, signing 13 players and selling 15 in his first 18 months at the club.<ref name=taylor/> On 25 February 2011, Bruce signed an extension to his contract, keeping him at Sunderland until 2014, with chairman [[Niall Quinn]] stating that \"In only 18 months he has reshaped our squad beyond recognition, bringing in some fantastically talented players. He embodies the ethos of teamwork and the importance of camaraderie in creating a wonderful spirit of togetherness amongst the players and staff\".<ref name=taylor>{{cite news |last1=Taylor |first1=Louise |title=Steve Bruce commits to Sunderland with new deal to 2014 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2011/feb/25/steve-bruce-sunderland-new-deal |accessdate=22 November 2015 |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |date=25 February 2011}}</ref>\n\nBruce was dismissed as manager on 30 November 2011, with Sunderland in 16th position following a poor run of form which culminated with a 2\u20131 home defeat to bottom club Wigan four days earlier.<ref>{{cite news |title=Black Cats sack Bruce |url=http://www.skysports.com/story/0,,12040_7343417,0.html |publisher=Sky Sports |date=30 November 2011 |accessdate=13 February 2012}}</ref> He later linked his dismissal from the managerial post with the fact that he is a fan of Newcastle United, Sunderland's [[Tyne\u2013Wear derby|bitter rivals]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espnfc.com/story/1044893/steve-bruce-blames-hatred-for-sunderland-dismissal |title=Steve Bruce blames 'hatred' for Sunderland dismissal |publisher=ESPN FC |date=5 April 2012 |accessdate=3 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Hull City===\nOn 8 June 2012, Bruce was appointed as manager at Championship club [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]] on a three-year contract.<ref name=\"Steve Bruce appointed Hull City manager on three-year deal\">{{cite news |title=Steve Bruce appointed Hull City manager on three-year deal |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/18192719 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=8 June 2012 |accessdate=10 January 2016}}</ref> In his first season with the club, he led them to promotion to the Premier League, clinching second place in the Championship on the final day of the season.<ref>{{cite news |title=Hull City promoted: Steve Bruce says players deserve success |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/22414814 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=4 May 2013 |accessdate=4 May 2013}}</ref> The following season, the \"Tigers\" came 16th with a club record tally of 37 points,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Darling |first1=Kevin |title=Hull 0\u20132 Everton |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27273312 |accessdate=22 November 2015 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=11 May 2014}}</ref> and reached the final of the FA Cup for the first time.<ref>{{cite news |title=Hull City 5\u20133 Sheffield United |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/26908665 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=13 April 2014 |accessdate=16 April 2014}}</ref> They took a two-goal lead in the first ten minutes of [[2014 FA Cup Final|the final]], but opponents Arsenal scored a goal in each half to take the game into extra-time and then scored a third to win the trophy.<ref name=\"Arsenal 3-2 Hull City\">{{cite news |title=Arsenal 3\u20132 Hull City |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/27354148 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=17 May 2014 |accessdate=17 May 2014}}</ref> Reaching the final qualified Hull for the [[2014\u201315 UEFA Europa League]], their first European campaign.<ref>{{cite news |last=Edwards |first=Luke |title=Hull City Premier League season 2014/15 guide |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/hull-city/11018676/Hull-City-Premier-League-season-guide-201415.html |accessdate=22 November 2015 |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |date=15 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2015, Bruce signed a three-year contract extension.<ref>{{cite news |title=Steve Bruce confirms signing new three-year deal with Hull City |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/31870162 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=13 March 2015 |accessdate=13 March 2015}}</ref> A run of poor form left Hull near the bottom of the table going into the final game of the [[2014\u201315 in English football|2014\u201315]] season and needing to defeat Bruce's former club Manchester United to stand any chance of avoiding relegation.<ref>{{cite news |title=Relegation battle: Can Hull repeat escape at Newcastle's expense? |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/32855534 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=22 May 2015 |accessdate=24 May 2015 |first=James |last=McMath}}</ref> They could only manage a 0\u20130 draw and were relegated to the Championship. The poor performances of a number of players signed by Bruce, including club record signing [[Abel Hern\u00e1ndez]], were identified as key factors in the club's failure to remain in the Premier League.<ref>{{cite news |title=Steve Bruce: Hull manager admits his side 'were not good enough' |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/32870902 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=24 May 2015 |accessdate=24 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2016, Bruce won the [[EFL Championship Manager of the Month|Championship Manager of the Month]] after leading Hull to four victories; Hern\u00e1ndez, who scored six times, got the [[EFL Championship Player of the Month|players' equivalent]].<ref name=\"Hull's Steve Bruce and Abel Hernandez land January's Sky Bet Championship awards\">{{cite news |last1=Crellin |first1=Mark |title=Hull's Steve Bruce and Abel Hernandez land January's Sky Bet Championship awards |url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/10155856/hulls-steve-bruce-and-abel-hernandez-land-januarys-sky-bet-championship-awards |accessdate=15 March 2016 |publisher=Sky Sports |date=5 February 2016}}</ref> Hull finished the season in fourth, qualifying for [[2016 Football League play-offs|the play-offs]], where they defeated Derby County in the semi-finals. In the final on 28 May, a 25-yard goal from [[Mohamed Diam\u00e9]] against Sheffield Wednesday won Hull promotion to the Premier League for the second time during Bruce's spell in charge. Bruce said after the game that he had considered resignation following the team's relegation, and would hold talks with the prospective new owners to be assured of his future.<ref>{{cite news |title=Hull City promoted: Steve Bruce will take time to consider future as manager |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/36407168 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=28 May 2016 |accessdate=29 May 2016}}</ref> In July 2016, with his future at Hull seemingly still uncertain, he was interviewed by officials of [[The Football Association]] concerning the vacant position of manager of England.<ref>{{cite news |title=Steve Bruce: Hull boss holds England manager talks |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/36832548 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=19 July 2016 |accessdate=19 July 2016}}</ref> Three days later, Bruce met with Hull City officials and announced his resignation later that day<ref>{{cite news |title=Steve Bruce: Hull City manager leaves newly promoted club |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/36868495 |publisher=BBC Sport |date=22 July 2016 |accessdate=22 July 2016}}</ref> amid claims he became frustrated by a lack of transfer activity at the club.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bruce leaves Hull City by mutual consent |url=http://theworldgame.sbs.com.au/article/2016/07/23/bruce-leaves-hull-city-mutual-consent |website=The World Game |publisher=Special Broadcasting Service |accessdate=23 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Aston Villa===\nOn 12 October 2016, Bruce was appointed manager of Championship club Aston Villa.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/37610020 |title=Aston Villa: Steve Bruce appointed manager of Championship club |publisher=BBC Sport |date=12 October 2016 |accessdate=12 October 2016}}</ref> In his second match in charge, Villa defeated [[Reading F.C.|Reading]], the club's first win in 11 games and the first away win for 14 months.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/37614900 |title=Reading 1\u20132 Aston Villa |publisher=BBC Sport |date=19 October 2016 |accessdate=19 October 2016}}</ref> He brought in [[Colin Calderwood]] as assistant manager from [[Brighton & Hove Albion]] and [[Stephen Clemence]] from old club Hull City as first-team coach.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11677/10615824/aston-villa-name-stephen-clemence-as-first-team-coach-as-trio-exit |title=Aston Villa name Stephen Clemence as first-team coach as trio exit |publisher=Sky Sports |date=13 October 2016 |accessdate=23 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://m.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/38021312 |title=Colin Calderwood: Aston Villa announce ex-Brighton coach as assistant manager |publisher=BBC Sport |date=21 November 2016 |accessdate=23 January 2017}}</ref> In the [[2017\u201318 in English football|2017\u201318]] season, Villa secured a play-off place and defeated Middlesbrough to reach [[2018 EFL Championship play-off Final|the final]],<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44035613 |title=Aston Villa 0\u20130 Middlesbrough |publisher=BBC Sport |date=15 May 2018 |accessdate=16 May 2018}}</ref> but lost 1\u20130 to [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] in the final and thus missed out on promotion to the Premier League.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/44178427 |title=Aston Villa 0\u20131 Fulham |publisher=BBC Sport |date=26 May 2018 |accessdate=28 May 2018}}</ref> On 2 October 2018, Villa surrendered a two-goal lead, drawing 3\u20133 at home to bottom club [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]]. One spectator threw a cabbage at Bruce and there were calls from home fans on the [[Holte End]] for Bruce to go.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45634934 |title=Aston Villa 3\u20133 Preston: Steve Bruce confirms fan threw cabbage |date=2 October 2018 |publisher=BBC Sport |accessdate=3 October 2018}}</ref> The following day, he was sacked by Villa after a poor run of form.<ref>{{cite web |title=Steve Bruce sacked by Aston Villa |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11677/11516430/steve-bruce-sacked-by-aston-villa |publisher=Sky Sports |accessdate=3 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Sheffield Wednesday===\nIn January 2019, Bruce was appointed manager of Championship club [[Sheffield Wednesday F.C.|Sheffield Wednesday]] with effect from the start of the following month.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/46660813 |title=Steve Bruce: Sheffield Wednesday appoint new manager |publisher=BBC Sport |date=2 January 2019 |accessdate=2 January 2019}}</ref> On 27 January, his delay in taking up this appointment was criticised by ''[[Match of the Day]]'' pundits [[Danny Murphy (footballer, born 1977)|Danny Murphy]] and [[Ruud Gullit]] during a 3\u20130 FA Cup defeat away to Chelsea.<ref>{{cite news |last1=de Menezes |first1=Jack |title=BBC pundits Danny Murphy and Ruud Gullit criticise Steve Bruce for taking break despite recent death of both parents, prompting anger from son |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/fa-league-cups/alex-bruce-tweet-danny-murphy-ruud-gullit-steve-bruce-sheffield-wednesday-break-manager-start-job-a8749746.html |accessdate=29 January 2019 |work=The Independent |date=28 January 2019}}</ref> Bruce subsequently defended his decision, as he had had two operations since leaving Aston Villa and needed time to recuperate, as well as the need to recover from the death of both his parents in 2018.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Edwards |first1=Luke |title=Steve Bruce defends decision to delay start as Sheffield Wednesday manager for Barbados holiday |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2019/01/28/steve-bruce-defends-decision-delay-start-sheffield-wednesday/ |accessdate=29 January 2019 |work=Daily Telegraph |date=29 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Newcastle United===\n[[BBC Sport]] reported in July 2019 that Bruce had resigned from his position at Wednesday,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48989831 |title=Steve Bruce: Sheffield Wednesday boss resigns amid Newcastle United interest |first=Simon |last=Stone |publisher=BBC Sport |date=15 July 2019 |accessdate=16 July 2019}}</ref> after he earlier admitted that he had held talks with Premier League [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] over their managerial vacancy.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48976404 |title=Steve Bruce: Newcastle United hold talks with Sheffield Wednesday manager |publisher=BBC Sport |date=13 July 2019 |accessdate=16 July 2019}}</ref> His appointment at Newcastle was confirmed on 17 July.<ref name=\"newcastle-appoint\"/> Sheffield Wednesday, however, soon filed a report to the Premier League alleging misconduct in his appointment,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2019/07/17/steve-bruce-confirmed-newcastle-uniteds-new-head-coach-three/ |title= Sheffield Wednesday respond angrily to Steve Bruce's confirmation as new Newcastle head coach|website=The Telegraph |author=Luke Edwards |date= 17 July 2019| accessdate=23 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2019/07/22/sheffield-wednesday-report-newcastle-premier-league-steve-bruce/ |title= Sheffield Wednesday report Newcastle to Premier League over Steve Bruce appointment |website=The Telegraph |date= 22 July 2019| accessdate=23 July 2019}}</ref> stating that there were still outstanding legal issues with Bruce having resigned just 48 hours earlier, whilst also suspecting that confidential details of Bruce's contract were leaked making it impossible for him to remain at the club.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11703/11769477/steve-bruce-contract-details-leaked-to-newcastle-sheffield-wednesday-believe |title=Steve Bruce contract details leaked to Newcastle, Sheffield Wednesday believe |website=Sky Sports |date= 24 July 2019| accessdate=25 July 2019}}</ref> Newcastle United denied any wrongdoing and stated that they were confident no case could be escalated.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2019/07/21/newcastle-confident-have-no-legal-case-answer-appointment-steve/ |title= Newcastle confident they have no legal case to answer in appointment of Steve Bruce|website=The Telegraph |author=Luke Edwards |date= 21 July 2019| accessdate=23 July 2019}}</ref> Reaction from the fans was mixed, with some feeling Bruce would not achieve the standard set by predecessor [[Rafa Ben\u00edtez]], whilst his recent lack of Premier League football and management of rival club Sunderland proved controversial.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.express.co.uk/sport/football/1156031/Jonjo-Shelvey-Newcastle-transfer-news-Steve-Bruce-Rafa-Benitez-Mike-Ashley-Yoshinori-Muto |title=Jonjo Shelvey pleads with Newcastle fans after controversial Steve Bruce appointment |website=Daily Express |publisher=Daily Express |date= 21 July 2019| accessdate=22 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2019/07/19/stevebruce-hits-back-suggestions-will-mike-ashleys-newcastle/ |title=Steve Bruce hits back at suggestions he will be Mike Ashley's Newcastle puppet: 'I will have the final say on transfers' |website=The Telegraph |author=Luke Edwards |date=19 July 2019| accessdate=22 July 2019}}</ref> Bruce acknowledged Ben\u00edtez's popularity and stated he hoped the fans would not rush to judgement and give him time to prove himself.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11678/11778838/newcastle-boss-steve-bruce-says-rafa-benitez-will-be-difficult-to-follow |title=Newcastle boss Steve Bruce says Rafa Benitez will be difficult to follow |website=Sky Sports |author=Dan Sansom |date=6 August 2019| accessdate=7 August 2019}}</ref> Due to [[Visa policy of China|visa problems in China]], Bruce watched his first match as manager from the stands which saw Newcastle achieve a third-place finish in the pre-season [[2019 Premier League Asia Trophy]] following a 1-0 victory over [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]].<ref name=\"Shanghai\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49056793 |title=Newcastle 1-0 West Ham: Steve Bruce watches from stands as Magpies win in Shanghai |website=BBC Sport |publisher=BBC |date= 20 July 2019| accessdate=22 July 2019}}</ref> Bruce soon made six signings,<ref>{{cite news |title= Premier League ins and outs: The 2019 summer transfer window moves |url= https://www.skysports.com/transfer/news/12691/11713244/premier-league-ins-and-outs-all-the-2019-summer-transfer-window-moves |accessdate=14 August 2019 |publisher=Sky Sports |date=9 August 2019}}</ref> notably securing [[Joelinton Cassio Apolin\u00e1rio de Lira|Joelinton]] from [[TSG 1899 Hoffenheim]] for \u00a340 million, breaking the club's transfer fee record previously set by the purchase of [[Miguel Almir\u00f3n]] for \u00a321 million six months earlier.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11678/11769091/newcastle-sign-joelinton-from-hoffenheim-in-40m-club-record-deal |title= Newcastle sign Joelinton from Hoffenheim in \u00a340m club-record deal| website=Sky Sports| author=Lyall Thomas| date= 18 July 2019| accessdate=24 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title= Newcastle break club record to sign \u00a321m Miguel Almir\u00f3n from Atlanta |url= https://www.theguardian.com/football/2019/jan/31/newcastle-break-club-transfer-record-sign-miguel-almiron-atlanta-united-fc-transfer-window-football |accessdate=31 January 2019 |publisher=The Guardian |date=31 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Life outside football==\n===Personal life===\nBruce has been married since February 1983 to Janet (n\u00e9e Smith),<ref name=\"express\">{{cite news |first=Steve |last=Millar |title=Fan's stick made Bruce a pig |url=http://express.lineone.net/posts/view/6318 |newspaper=Daily Express |location=London |date=6 May 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090630155255/http://express.lineone.net/posts/view/6318 |archivedate=30 June 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"irish\">{{cite news |title=Morrison seals it for Brummies |newspaper=Irish Examiner |location=Cork |date=24 February 2003 |url=http://archives.tcm.ie/irishexaminer/2003/02/24/story432371430.asp |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030821012911/http://archives.tcm.ie/irishexaminer/2003/02/24/story432371430.asp |archivedate=21 August 2003 |first=John |last=Curtis |quote=...it's a nice way for me to celebrate my 20th wedding anniversary}}</ref><ref>Bruce (1994), p. 66.</ref> who is also from the [[Hexham]] area, and went to the same school as Bruce.<ref name=\"SB38\" /> The couple have two children, [[Alex Bruce (footballer, born 1984)|Alex]] (born 1984) and Amy (born 1987).<ref name=\"express\" /> Alex is also a footballer, and was signed by his father for Hull City in July 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/19046881 |title=Hull City bring in defender Alex Bruce |publisher=BBC Sport |date=30 July 2012 |accessdate=30 July 2012}}</ref> He had previously played under his father's management at Birmingham City, but left the club in 2006, in part due to accusations of [[nepotism]] levelled at his father.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bruce Jnr heads for fresh fields |newspaper=Birmingham Post |date=3 August 2006 |url=http://www.birminghampost.co.uk/news/local-news/bruce-jnr-heads-fresh-fields-3978796 |accessdate=11 September 2008}}</ref> Amy was linked romantically with Aston Villa player [[Lee Hendrie]] in tabloid newspaper stories in 2004, which provoked an angry response from her father, who described the reports as \"lies\", and claimed that journalists had gone so far as to contact his doctor and examine his household waste in an attempt to uncover gossip.<ref name=\"Lee2\">{{cite news |first=Colin |last=Tattum |title=Bruce in rage over \"lies\" |url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-123252662.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503105452/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-123252662.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=3 May 2016 |newspaper=Birmingham Evening Mail |date=16 October 2004 |accessdate=28 February 2016 |via=Highbeam Research |url-access=subscription }}</ref> In September 2004, Bruce was involved in an altercation outside his home with two men who were attempting to steal his daughter's car. The affray left him with facial injuries but did not prevent him from travelling to a Premier League match the same day.<ref name=\"bruise\">{{cite news |title=Steve Bruise |newspaper=Sunday Mirror |location=London |date=26 September 2004 |url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/STEVE+BRUISE%3B+Soccer+boss+battered+by+yobs+who+tried+to+steal...-a0122508811 |accessdate=27 September 2007 |first=Andy |last=Gardner}}</ref> After the incident one newspaper attempted to connect it with the allegations concerning Hendrie, leading Bruce to contemplate legal action.<ref name=\"Lee2\" />\n\n===Other activities===\nBruce's autobiography, ''Heading for Victory'', was published in 1994. In 1999, while manager of Huddersfield, he wrote a trio of novels: ''Striker!'', ''Sweeper!'' and ''Defender!''. The books centred on fictional football manager Steve Barnes, based on Bruce, who solved murder mysteries and thwarted terrorists. Bruce later expressed his embarrassment at the books, which have become sought-after collectables.<ref>{{cite news |last1=McCauley |first1=Ciaran |title=Steve Bruce: Inside the literary career of Aston Villa's manager |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-37877150 |accessdate=12 June 2018 |publisher=BBC News |date=5 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Steve Bruce still cringes at his 'laughing stock' novels |url=https://www.eurosport.co.uk/football/steve-bruce-still-cringes-at-his-laughing-stock-novels_sto4713697/story.shtml |accessdate=12 June 2018 |publisher=Eurosport |date=22 November 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Playing statistics==\n{|class=wikitable style=text-align:center\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and comp